      "properties": {},
      "widgets_values": ["REMOVE-THEN-REPLACE - the one workflow that uses BOTH Moebius and FLUX.2 Klein together\n\nUse this when you want to REPLACE an existing object with something specific: paint the object once, Moebius erases it to a clean background (the 'clean plate'), then FLUX.2 generates the replacement into that cleaned region from your prompt.\n\nWhy chain them (instead of just FLUX alone)? FLUX's ReferenceLatent feeds the WHOLE source image back in as edit context - including the object you are trying to get rid of. At the 4-step distilled setting that context tends to 'echo' the old object (ghost shapes, colours bleeding through). By removing it with Moebius FIRST and feeding the CLEANED image as FLUX's base + context, FLUX no longer fights the ghost of what was there. For pure ADD-to-empty-space this is unnecessary (use the standalone FLUX graph); for REPLACE it is a real quality win.\n\nData flow:\n  Load Image + paint mask\n     |-> Moebius Inpaint  (mask -> erase object, clean background)  ---.\n     |                                                                  v\n     '-> (same mask) ------------------------------> Inpaint Crop (of the CLEANED image)\n                                                        -> FLUX.2 inpaint (your prompt) -> Inpaint Stitch -> Save\n\nThe SAME painted mask drives both stages: 'this thing -> gone -> put X here'.\n\nMODELS: Moebius auto-downloads (~1 GB). FLUX needs flux-2-klein-9b-fp8 (diffusion_models), qwen_3_8b_fp8mixed (text_encoders), flux2-vae (vae).\nEXTRA NODE PACK (FLUX half only): ComfyUI-Inpaint-CropAndStitch by lquesada (https://github.com/lquesada/ComfyUI-Inpaint-CropAndStitch)."],
      "color": "#332",
      "bgcolor": "#553",
      "title": "About this workflow"
    },
